then proceeds:]   The very hour that I found myself in a place of safety, I took pen to write to you.
When I began, I designed only to write six or eight lines, to inquire after your health: for, having heard nothing from you, I feared indeed, that you had been, and still were, too ill to write.
But no sooner did pen begin to blot the paper, but my sad heart hurried the paper into length.
The apprehensions I had lain under, that I should not be able to get away; the fatigue I had in effecting my escape: the difficulty of procuring a lodging for myself; having disliked the people of two houses, and those of a third disliking me; for you must think I made a frighted appearance--these, together with the recollection of what I had suffered from him, and my farther apprehensions of my insecurity, and my desolate circumstances, had so disordered me, that I remember I rambled strangely in the letter of his friend Belford.
In short, I thought the letter of his friend Belford, on re-perusal, a half-distracted one: but I then despaired, (were I to begin again,) of writing better: so I let the letter of his friend Belford go: and can have no excuse for directing the letter of his friend Belford as I did, if the cause of the incoherence in the letter of his friend Belford will not furnish me with a very pitiable one.
