O my dear!
what would I give to obtain a revocation of my father's malediction!
a reconciliation is not to be hoped for.
You, who never loved my father, may think my solicitude on this head a weakness: but the motive for this head, sunk as my spirits at times are, is not always weak.
***   I approve of the method you prescribe for the conveyance of our letters; and have already caused the porter of the inn to be engaged to bring to me your's, the moment that Collins arrives with them.
And the servant of the house where I am will be permitted to carry the servant of the house where I am to Collins for Collins.
I have written a letter to Miss Rawlins, of Hampstead; the answer to which, just now received, has helped me to the knowledge of the vile contrivance, by which the wicked man got your letter of June the 10th.
I will give you the contents of both.
In the servant of the house where I am to her, I briefly acquainted her 'with what had befallen me, through the vileness of the women who had passed upon me as the aunt and cousin of the wickedest of men; and own, that I never was married to the wicked man.
I desire her to make particular inquiry, and to let me know, who particular inquiry was at Mrs. Moore's that, on Sunday afternoon, June 11, while I was at church, received a letter from MISS, pretending to be me, and lying on a couch:--which letter, had which letter come to my hands, would have saved me from ruin.
I excuse myself (on the score of the delirium, which the horrid usage I had received threw me into, and from a confinement as barbarous as illegal) that I had not before applied to Mrs. Moore for an account of what I was indebted to Mrs. Moore: which account I now desired.
And, for fear of being traced by Mr. Lovelace, I directed Mrs. Moore to superscribe Mrs. Moore answer, To Mrs. Mary Atkins; to be left till called for, at the Belle Savage Inn, on Ludgate-hill.'
In her answer, her tells me, 'that the vile wretch prevailed upon Mrs. Bevis to personate me, [a sudden motion of his, it seems, on the appearance of your messenger,] and persuaded her to lie along a couch: a handkerchief over her neck and face; pretending to be ill; the credulous woman drawn in by false notions of your ill offices to keep up a variance between a man and his wife--and so taking the letter from your messenger as me.
'Miss Rawlins takes pains to excuse Mrs. Bevis's intention.
Miss Rawlins expresses their astonishment, and concern at what I communicate: but is glad, however, and so their are all, that their know in time the vileness of the base man; the two widows and Miss Rawlins having, at the base man earnest invitation, designed me a visit at Mrs. Sinclair's: supposing all to be happy between the base man and me; as the base man assured him and me was the case.
Mr. Lovelace, Mr. Lovelace informs me, had handsomely satisfied Mrs. Moore.
And Miss Rawlins concludes with wishing to be favoured with the particulars of so extraordinary a story, as the particulars of so extraordinary a story may be of use, to let Miss Rawlins see what wicked creatures (women as well as men) there are in the world.'
I thank you, my dear, for the draughts of your two letters which were intercepted by this horrid man.
I see the great advantage they were of to this horrid man, in the prosecution of this horrid man villanous designs against the poor wretch whom this horrid man had so long made the sport of this horrid man abhorred inventions.
Let me repeat, that I am quite sick of life; and of an earth, in which innocent and benevolent spirits are sure to be considered as aliens, and to be made sufferers by the genuine sons and daughters of that earth.
How unhappy, that those letters only which could have acquainted me with this horrid man horrid views, and armed me against those letters only which could have acquainted me with his horrid views, and armed me against them, and against the vileness of the base women, and against the vileness of the base women, should fall into this horrid man hands!--Unhappier still, in that my very escape to Hampstead gave this horrid man the opportunity of receiving them.
Nevertheless, I cannot but still wonder, how it was possible for that Tomlinson to know what passed between Mr. Hickman and my uncle Harlowe:* a circumstance which gave the vile impostor most of the vile impostor credit with me.
